<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1923-07-21T12:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1923-07-21T12:00:00-05:00" n="936" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d936">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">711.672/124: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the <gloss type="to">Special Mission at Lausanne</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1923-07-21T13:00:00-04:00"><hi rend="italic">July 21,
                                        1923—1 p.m.</hi></date></dateline></opener>
                        <p>252. The views expressed in Mission’s 548 of July 21, and especially the
                            statements you made to Ismet and reported in the first paragraph are
                            fully approved by the Department. You should endeavor to <pb facs="1231" n="1107" xml:id="pg_1107"/> meet every reasonable request of the
                            Turks and use the utmost patience in your dealings. But as you have
                            indicated in your telegram, the Department would not wish you to give
                            consideration to a treaty which leaves fundamental issues for later
                            settlement.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Hughes</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>